<Author>ap663
<Content>Exceeded expectations (wheelchair access details inside!) I booked this hotel because they were offering a great deal with a hefty resort credit and only $15 for an upgrade to a junior suite which my friend and I couldn't resist. I was a little nervous after reading the reviews here, but we wanted a nice place to stay on the beach that would provide us with two beds to sleep in and that was in a quiet area. The resort by far exceeded my expectations.Our suite looked like it was remodeled in the last couple of years and everything was fresh and clean with a partial view of the ocean and beach. We had a king bed and a pull-out sofa in our sitting area and both were comfortable. While the shower wasn't a roll-in, the tub was low enough to make transferring from my chair easy and the grab bars were well placed. The hotel was able to provide a good shower chair which was brought up within minutes of it being requested. The carpet was a bit thick, which made pushing a bit hard but I got used to it.Wheelchair access in the resort was very good but everything is up three steps. So any time I wanted to go to a different section of the property I had to use a vertical lift. There are also two verticle lifts (one with a rather tight side turn, four wheel scoooters beware) at the entrance of the hotel. The front desk gave me a key to the lifts to use for the duration of my stay, which was convenient as I didn't have to wait for a staff member to come and help me, though most of the time someone ran up the second I approached a lift and offered their assistance which was nice. I have mixed feelings about recommending this hotel to other wheelchair users because it is perfectly accessible as long as the lifts work properly. If one breaks down then you would likely lose access to that part of the property. Luckily they all worked just fine for the duration of my stay but that's always the risk with mechanical chair lifts. The public bathrooms all have huge wheelchair accessible stalls and the bathroom by the pool has an accessible stall and an accessible roll-in shower with grab bars - but no bench and no doors on either the shower or toilet stall. The beach access path is hard sand and there's a sign saying you can take wheelchairs and strollers on that path but I didn't want to risk getting sand in my casters so I didn't go out on the beach. It would be nice if they put down some plastic meshing for wheelchair users. The hotel has a ramp going down to the beach path though so I think the beach path may be public property since it's a public beach.Overall service was excellent. The answer to pretty much any request was yes. The staff was super friendly, especially the waiters at the Hibiscus Restaurant where we got breakfast every day. We also loved lounging by the pool and playing board games and being showered with freebies once an hour (the pool attendants bring out fresh fruit skewers, smoothies, and wet towels once an hour). The only bad thing about the property is that there's nothing around except for other resorts and condos so food choices are limited. The prices in the hotel restaurants for breakfast and lunch weren't ridiculous and the food was pretty good so we didn't mind eating there. The good restaurants in South Beach are about a 15 minute bus ride away and there's a bus stop right across the street from the hotel. 
