<Author>RollTide05
<Content>Poor Poor Miami Beach Resort and Spa! We booked our reservations with the resort in December for our vacation/conference in April. We had no problems with the booking agents and were actually looking forward to our trip! Counting down months turned to weeks until finally we counted down days. Being so close to our travel date, we decided to call the resort with some last minute questions and spa reservations and were given clear, positive responses. 2 or 3 days before our travel we decided to search for reviews of the resort. Stomach churning was the best way to describe our feelings after reading the reviews on this site. With too little time to cancel and re-book, we prepared ourselves for the worst. When we arrived in Miami, we drove past restaurants and beautiful resorts on Collins Ave. As we continued to drive, we noticed the restaurants diminished and the resorts began to look aged. We pulled up to the MBRS and were not overly impressed with its outward appearance, but were not horrified as so many reviewers seemed to be. The bellmen were helpful, and persistent despite telling them I could manage my bags (being prepared for the worst of course, I wanted to hold tight to my personal possessions just in case) and the person behind the check in counter was a young and somewhat unprofessional gentleman. We got our room keys, towel cards (more on that later) and mini bar keys and headed to our room. My husband and I held our breath when the elevator door opened and we walked to the room. The door opened into a hallway where you could see the bed, a desk and one very large window. Around the corner was the television and a sitting chair and another large window. Behind the front door was a very tiny, very dark and very dated bathroom. The picture on their site, no way! Not the same at all. Many of the pictures on the site give it way more credit than deserved. There was quite a bit of hair to be found throughout, (none of which was mine, different color and all) on the floor, in the tub and on some of our towels. The furnishings were hands down dated and out of style. You could tell many a wet behind had sat on the armchair and the carpet was kind of gross. The bed linens are in need of replacing and the mattress, well bad backs are not soothed here. Shoes are recommended throughout. Our view was interesting. We could see part of the bay, part of the beach and a lot of the resort next door under construction. It was very noisy and very unattractive, but what can you do? Overall the room was eclectic, the storage was great, the decor was fascinating, especially the gigantic door pulls but it needs some modernizing. The room doors are very heavy so you can hear slamming quite frequently. It is not a good hotel for an afternoon siesta. Housekeeping will likely not leave you alone despite the Privacy Please sign. We ventured to the pool area and found it decently equipped. Cushions and chairs were readily available, although by the afternoon only about 10 chairs were in the sun and the rest were in the shade for the rest of the day. The towels were given out in exchange for a towel card which if you lost it or the towel you were forced to pay $15. I would not have stolen the towel if it was the last towel on earth. It was very thin, worn around the edges and only good enough to dry of your big toe. We bought another one at CVS to get me through the week. The amenities at the pool were nice, small juice sample and cold washcloth in the morning, bar snack mix in the afternoon. We ate 3 meals on our own at the resort during our 5 day stay and found the food decent, but the price a little inflated. Our service was excellent, the staff made an effort to strike up conversation and remembered us when we returned. Try the key lime pie, you won't be sorry. Breakfast is expensive, dinner and drinks are expensive, bottom line. When we did eat out, we got great recommendations from the concierges Luis and Eduardo and we rarely had to wait for a taxi outside. The bellmen were really good. We did rent a car for 2 days but ended up taking it back because it was not worth the $22 a day valet charge with all of the other resort charges. Some of the additional charges included internet, whether you paid $10 for wireless in your room or $5.00 + $0.30/minute in the business center it wasn't free, $5 for a chair and $15 for an umbrella on the beach, 18% gratuity everywhere, a daily resort fee, and $20 mini bar removal charge (keep it locked, not worth it to move). It was hard being so far from other restaurants and the taxi fares are not cheap. All in all, my husband and I had a good trip. We were worried, with some good reason, but we tried to see past it. For what we paid and for the location, give me a pool and the beach and I am happy, we were okay with it. We will definitely look for other resorts, if we go back to Miami, but it has character and some interesting quirks. We felt taken care of and were provided with a decent place to stay. If you go, be open minded and as another reviewer mentioned, if you want to be in the lap of luxury go somewhere else. If you want to have the best of the best, this is not it. But if you want a safe, mostly quiet, and eclectic hotel, stay here. 
