<Author>kMacNYC
<Content>Very disappointed - don't recommend No idea how people could rate this a good hotel. Especially since it鈥檚 billed at a 4-star. Perhaps I could delude myself it was fine if I felt it was a 2-star and I got a bargain鈥ut not for this price. Was really disappointed especially since we were taking my husband鈥檚 parents there for vacation from their home in rainy Dublin, Ireland. I felt it was far too expensive for the value. Every single amenity was individually priced. Parking was $22 per night. Internet connection was a minimum of $13. We found an internet caf茅 downtown that cost us $2.00 for 10 minutes. I know it鈥檚 hard deciphering which reviews to rely on. I am an adamant researcher myself - almost obsessive-compulsive about cross-referencing several travel websites for reliable info on hotels, i.e. Frommers, Fodors, Trip Advisor, Travelocity, Expedia, Hotels.com. If you check more than 3 sites saying a place is good or bad - it gives you the ability to get a median idea - toss out the 鈥渢his is the greatest place on earth鈥?and the 鈥渢his is the worst hotel ever鈥?comments and you arrive somewhere near the truth of the matter. Let me first say I have yet to complain about any one of my hotel stays in either Europe, America or Mexico. I鈥檓 in my early 30鈥檚  have stayed in Paris, Rome, Munich, Dublin, D.C., West Palm, Texas, Miami, Cape Cod, L.A., San Fran, Turks  Caicos, Puerto Rico, St. Kitts, Grand Bahama  Paradise Island, and various locales in Mexico. That being said I would like to warn others about this hotel. I listed those locales to merely say that my stay at MBRS for the price - was well NOT worth it. There is NO way this hotel deserves a 4 star rating. I have never had a problem with any hotel I have every stayed at that was billed as a 3 star hotel or higher. I鈥檝e stayed in 2 star hotels /motels that had better service than the Miami Beach Resort  Spa. When the word resort is placed in the name of a hotel you expect high quality. I brought my in-laws who flew in from Dublin to this hotel in the expectation that with a billing of 鈥渞esort,鈥?a title which they are accustomed to for beach resort locales in Europe, it would be full of amenities. If I had chosen simply a hotel I would have expected just room and perhaps a hotel bar. The most impressive feature about this hotel is the lobby. Exquisite marble and chandeliers - very neat and orderly reservation desk. However, one does not sleep in the lobby. The parking attendants, though harried, were very good about getting the car (except one day which took over 25 minutes to get my rental from the garage). I booked my trip package through Expedia for 2 rooms with a king-size bed. The check in was very smooth, we arrived earlier than the permissible 3pm and they were very amenable to get us checked in early. The bellmen were very pleasant. However our rooms were placed on separate floors, which in and of itself was not a problem and the lady at the desk did alert us to this fact. Funnily enough the desk clerk offered us a mini-bar key which we declined but when we got to the room there was no mini-bar. My husband鈥檚 parents stayed on the 10th floor with a partial view of the ocean and bay. We were put on the 4th floor in a newly renovated room which happens to be eye level with the extended roof - so if you picture a ceiling to floor window the tiled floor of our hotel room (no rug) was on level with the rooftop of the 3rd floor mezzanine - giving us an unsightly grayish black roof. Beyond the roof view was a partial view of the ocean and directly across from our room was a high-rise condo complex who had a direct view of our room unless we fully dragged the floor to ceiling drapes closed - which of course then darkened the already unwell lit room. This room had been renovated to be uber-modern - sky blue walls and ceiling which was fine - an open floor plan so the bed was in the middle of the room a floating oak-ish looking closet so you could see past the bed into the bathroom area - no privacy at all. Not a lot of hanging space. Plenty of drawers but shallow so you can鈥檛 fit much. The shower was great - very modern - huge showerhead - the size of a soccer ball - with a floor to ceiling frosted door. The toilet also had a floor to ceiling frosted door - which was very un-conducive to privacy and tiny to get in and out of because of the way the door swung. The rectangular basin sink was interesting ( but didn鈥檛 drain well) and the mirror was large but they both perpendicularly abutted the shower which made difficult for 2 people getting ready at same time. The florescent lighting was so low you could barely see to put on make-up. There was no floor to ceiling mirror to check yourself out before you left the room. I鈥檓 all for modern but it also has to be functional. The maids came everyday to clean the room, but perhaps since our entire room was tiled, and I personally prefer rugs b/c I don鈥檛 like walking on tiles barefoot, I found that the area near the shower was not cleaned thoroughly. I have very long hair and would find daily hairs that were not picked up by either a mop or vacuum. Having said all that - the rooms were not a major problem with us. The in-law鈥檚 room, in contrast ,was lovely. More traditional - clean - large - nice views. So if you鈥檙e looking for a basic room w/o frills it鈥檚 not bad.In terms of service - I found, again, for a resort, it to be severely lacking in both it鈥檚 offerings and customer service. The only caveat was the front desk clerks which were all pleasant. The concierge however was a different experience all together. My husband鈥檚 birthday was on July 2nd and we were also down in Miami for the July 4th Holiday. The first night we were there I asked if there were any restaurants nearby because we were tired we didn鈥檛 feel like going to South Beach which is about a 7-10 minute ride depending on traffic. He coldly told us well there weren鈥檛 that many options. Now, at a resort, one would think you鈥檇 have someone who鈥檚 entire job is defined by his ability to offer service to customers. He made us feel like we were bothering him. I鈥檝e lived in NYC my entire life. I鈥檓 used to the haughtiness of some of the finer hotels/restaurants/bars. This place was certainly not worthy of such an attitude as one would expect at say the Ritz. I went to the concierge to ask if there were any good Cuban restaurants鈥is response鈥︹€漵ure.鈥?That鈥檚 it. I went to the concierge twice more to ask for advice on restaurants, things to do etc....when I asked if there were events going on for July 4th - he responded - of course w/o further explanation. It was like being a homicide detective trying to pry answers from the murderer. They have no guides to look at for restaurants or activities like most other resorts I've been to.If you want to fork over an exorbitant amount of money for sub-par food than stay here. I鈥檝e stayed at the Hyatt Resort - a 5 star hotel in Aruba - and there food was less expensive and 5 times better. The breakfast food for 2 people plus a 17% gratuity (which is automatically attributed to every single bill at the hotel whether you鈥檙e just ordering fries or a cocktail) cost us 39 dollars. Again, I live in NYC and 2 eggs over-easy with ham with one glass of OJ does not equal 39 dollars, it equals extortion. We had dinner at their restaurant which does have beautiful views overlooking the pool and Miami Beach. Each entr茅e was 25 dollars or more and it was horrid - and I鈥檓 not a finicky eater. I had mahi-mahi, as did my husband, which turned out looking and tasting like a overdone fish sandwich from a fast-food place. I ordered tuna sashimi as an appetizer - it鈥檚 hard to screw up raw fish - but they managed to do so. I didn鈥檛 even eat my meal. My husband - not a finicky either - ate it only because it was late and he was starving and we had no other course of action. His parents had steak - which was overcooked - and pasta which was like mush. The bill for 4 people was just shy of $300 and the food was awful. I wouldn鈥檛 have paid 10 dollars for the food that was served, so dishing out 25 dollars per dish was offensive. Do not eat at their restaurant. The pool bar is handy if you ready yourself for just finger food or bbq type of food - but again overpriced. One day the four of us had 4 Caesar salads, and 2 drinks each and it came to $125 - this place just literally left a bad taste in my mouth. You are held ransom here with such exorbitant prices b/c this hotel is located far off the main strip - 10 minutes north of south beach or any places to eat on Collins Avenue. My husband and I walked around one day in search of a deli b/c all we wanted was an iced tea and a sandwich - needless to say we walked down Collins and didn鈥檛 reach a deli until we hit south beach. Pool was fine - relatively long - not wide - but clean. Plenty of lounges and very comfortable cushions. Pool side restaurant was decent. Maybe 8 things on menu though so after 2 days you get sick of ordering a chicken sandwich with greasy fries, or a small burger or a 9 dollar salad. The wings were awful. It had fans hanging from rafters which constantly vacillate and mist water. I suppose this is supposed to keep you cool, but I found it annoying - you constantly feel damp while sitting there eating. Drinks were somewhat expensive (again I鈥檓 used to high prices in NYC) but it was $6 for domestic bottle of beer, $8 for mixed drinks and more if you wanted something off their standard cocktail menu - plus for every drink you order they bang you automatically 17% gratuity. I bartended in NYC and I found the gratuity ridiculous. Staff was friendly enough - if you could wave them down and if per chance they spoke English. I live in a melting pot city so I鈥檓 used to it but my Irish in-laws had trouble understanding what the staff was saying because everyone working as the wait staff, snack bar, or bartenders spoke broken English.Their snack shop charged $2.18 for a regular size cup of hot tea and close to 3 bucks for a stale bagel with nothing on it. In NYC you can get a bagel for 60 cents. If you wanted tea for room service it was $5 or $8 for a large cup of tea鈥?.for HOT WATER and a Lipton bag. Their wine was cheaper than hot water for $7. No vending machines in case you simply want a water or a soda.Location really not great. I鈥檝e stayed in Bal Harbor (about 10 min. north of this area) before and at least you could walk to restaurants or shops. Here you can get to a boardwalk via the beach 2 blocks down. The boardwalk is lovely and you can get a birds-eye view of other hotels. A long hike to get to any other restaurants. But beware there鈥檚 no escaping the sun. The beach was clean and there was a hut for wave- runners and other activities if you so desired. But if you wanted to lay out on the beach (which is a public beach) you had to pay for chairs and umbrellas. I think it was $5 for a chair and $15 for an umbrella - ridiculous. When you think you are going to a resort - you justly assume this is part of the resort fee - which they charge 10 dollars per room per day - plus tax per day of $1.30 - so for 5 days it was $56.50 each room. I鈥檓 sorry but I鈥檓 confused as to what this fee is for鈥s another reviewer said - for towels - which were threadbare?Bottom line-wouldn鈥檛 recommend to anyone -would never stay here again - it is way overpriced for what is offered-and I lived in NYC for decades, i.e. I鈥檓 used to high prices. As one reviewer said, 鈥淭he only thing remotely pleasant about this hotel was that we did not spend much time there.鈥?I second that notion. Most time we spent there was by the pool. 
