<Content>Wyndham Miami Beach-No Resort, but OK 3 star Wyndam Miami Beach Resort Currently here for a conference and was concerned prior to arrival given the previous reviews. I tried to keep and open mind and be objective for my own impressions. Upon arrival the lobby is pleasant and was rather busy. Other conferences were here and it was rather lively at the entrance where people were taking smoking breaks. Lobby is nicely appointed with stone/marble floor and small seating areas, though no grand lobby.  Upon check-in, we had to argue to get our reserved rate honored; we had to wait 15 minutes while the desk manager was called to rectify this. When then had to wait again to have the negotiated internet access, included in our package, honored. We did have to pay $8 for the in-room cable (so bring your own to avoid this cost). The attitude at the front desk seems to be we were getting the rate/internet access out of some largesse, when in fact I had THEIR printed confirmation of the rate/inclusions in black in white.  We did not received our promised welcome package (fruit, water, etc) but as this hotel does not participate in the 鈥淲yndham by Request鈥? that would explain the miserly attitude. We were not the only people at check in who were complaining. The front desk staff seemed to have their hands full with guest problems. The room was pleasant. We were 鈥渦pgraded鈥?to a 15th floor suite, meaning a slightly larger room with a sitting area and 2 banks of large north facing window (over looking a large construction project). We did have a side partial ocean view. It would have been nice if the hotel washed the exterior windows, as they were filthy (it hadn鈥檛 rained in nearly 4 months so it wasn鈥檛 just water spots from rain). The bed was comfortable and our request for firmer, foam pillows was quickly fulfilled. The room had a spacious seating area with four-arm chair and a sofa bed, coffee table, side tables. The work area was fine too- nice roomy desk next to another armchair and ottoman. The lighting in the room was rather dim, but I do appreciate the energy conservation attempts with the fluorescent bulbs in all the fixtures. If one incandescent light would remain at the desk for the work surface, that would be very helpful.  I could hear the elevator right next to our room, but even as a light sleeper, only used my earplugs one night. The furnishings are a bit dated and the mattress quilt is faded. The pool (no hot tub/Jacuzzi)  kiddie pool area are very nice and the fitness center is adequate 鈥?treadmills, weight machines, etc. There is a lot of storm/wind/water damage apparent at many, many properties up  down the beach. And a lot of demolition and construction, so perhaps that is why there鈥檚 no Jacuzzi?  The location on the beach is lovely for walking. The drawback to being in the 4800 of Collins is there are no restaurants/shops within easy walking distance. The closest on Arthur Godfrey are about 1.5 miles away - across the busy 6-lane boulevard of Collins Ave. We did use the (air-conditioned) buses up and down between North  South Beach, which are very quick and convenient on Collins.  All in all, we had a pleasant stay. Just keep your documentation for your negotiated rate, amenities, etc., be persistent and be advised that many of the staff are not adequately trained in customer service. I would not rate this hotel as a 鈥渞esort鈥?despite its title, more a 3 star hotel. My expectations were not high for this hotel and thus I was not disappointed. 
